==English==

===Etymology 1===
From Old English [[gemot]], ''[[meeting]]''

===Pronunciation===
*mo͞ot, /muːt/, /mu:t/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-uːt|Rhymes: -uːt]]

===Adjective===
'''moot''' {{notcomp}}

# {{law}} (USA) Without legal significance.
# Debateable, arguable, not settled
# Irrelevant, of no practical importance. (US English)

====Translations====
*German: [[hypothetisch]] (1,2), [[irrelevant]] (2)

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# (hist.) An [[assembly]] (usually for decision making in a locality) 
# {{law}} A [[hypothetical]] case argued by law students as an exercise; a [[moot case]]

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|moot||}}

# To bring up as a subject for [[debate]], to propose.
# To [[discuss]] or debate
# To make or declare [[irrelevant]] (US)

====Translations====
*German: [[zur]] [[Debatte]] [[stellen]] (1)

===Etymology 2===
Perhaps related to Swedish ''[[mutta]]''.
===Pronunciation===
*mo͝ot, /mʊt/, <tt>/mUt/</tt>
===Noun===
'''moot'''

# A meeting place for debate (historical) - see [[wikipedia:Moot Hall]].
# {{slang}} [[vagina|Vagina]].

